{{Expand French|Le Chêne de Flagey|date=July 2018}}
{{Infobox artwork|image=Gustave_Courbet_-_Le_chêne_de_Flagey.jpg|title=The Oak at Flagey|year=1864|museum=Musée Courbet|city=Paris|artist=Gustave Courbet}}
'''''The Oak at Flagey''''' (French - ''Le Chêne de Flagey'') or '''''The Vercingetorix Oak''''' (''Le Chêne de Vercingétorix'') is an 1864 landscape painting by [[Gustave Courbet]], measuring 89 by 110 cm. It shows an oak near the Courbet family farm in the village of [[Flagey, Doubs]], a few kilometres from [[Ornans]] in [[Franche-Comté]], named in relation to [[Vercingetorix]]. The oak was later struck by lightning and no longer survives.

In 1880 the artist's sister Juliette Courbet sold it to the banker [[Henry C. Gibson]] and on the latter's death it was offered to the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]] in 1896. It was sold at [[Sotheby's|Sotheby's New York]] in 1987 to a Japanese collector, [[Michimasa Murauchi]], for $450 000. It was then bought for 4.5 million Euros in 2012 by the [[musée Courbet]], including 2.7 million Euros from private donations and 1.3 million Euros from public funds. It was lent to the ''Volez, Voguez, Voyagez'' exhibition on [[Louis Vuitton]] at the [[Grand Palais]].

